snippet.textDisplay:
Youtube is the ideal job for a drug addict. You pretty much never have to leave the house. You can work whatever hours suit your habit if you're recording in advance. Makeup and lighting can hide a lot. You sit in front of a camera where you can edit and re-take. The rest of the time you're behind text. A combination of people making you feel bad about yourself and people feeling really good about yourself can bolster a habit in both ways at the same time. If you're the type of youtuber who just for whatever reason can't work a normal job and maybe has social/emotional issues (and I'm not judging... I'm glad they have a niche where they can still survive and give people something in that case,) then there is definitely going to be some real risk for falling into drugs or really, any number of bad, self-destructive habits. Because you easily can... if it crosses your mind.

Even though a youtuber has a 'public' job, they can actually operate in a very isolated, highly controlled space. You'd never know. And if anything, the image put out and mirrored back, along with general financial success, probably reinforces the idea that things are working out (or pushes the need for it to,) even if your habit is killing you.
